WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.480
Alright, so before we get to our next speaker, we all know that Dan Chen has spoken at every

00:00:05.480 --> 00:00:08.780
single conference we've had.

00:00:08.780 --> 00:00:12.160
But he's in England right now.

00:00:12.160 --> 00:00:15.640
And we're really upset about that because, you know, it breaks his streak.

00:00:15.640 --> 00:00:17.639
So we arranged for a special appearance...

00:00:17.639 --> 00:00:29.400
Wait for your song.

00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:32.400
They're playing O'Canada for you.

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:44.119
Okay, I won't make this go on too long.

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:47.040
So Dan recently had to relocate to Canada for a job.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:49.080
So he's really enjoying Canadian culture.

00:00:49.080 --> 00:00:52.759
You've gone curling and enjoying hockey and all that good stuff, right?

00:00:52.759 --> 00:00:55.279
Yeah, the Canucks are in the playoffs.

00:00:55.279 --> 00:00:56.279
There you go.

00:00:56.279 --> 00:01:01.880
Alright, so Dan is going to do a quick little short presentation in order to keep his streak

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:02.880
alive.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:03.880
Alright, yes.

00:01:03.880 --> 00:01:04.879
So welcome everyone.

00:01:04.879 --> 00:01:13.839
Sorry I can't be there in person, but this is just a quick little talk about the community

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:18.480
and my way to thank the community for the last 10 years.

00:01:18.480 --> 00:01:23.120
So for those who don't know me, I'm Daniel, I'm currently a postdoctoral teaching research

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:26.239
and teaching fellow at BC in Vancouver, Canada.

00:01:26.239 --> 00:01:29.239
So that's why I'm in Canada right now.

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:35.000
I'm also a data science educator at Posit and working mostly as like on their developer

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.019
advocacy team.

00:01:37.019 --> 00:01:40.360
And I also authored a book called Pandas for Everyone.

00:01:40.360 --> 00:01:45.080
So I've been doing a lot of our stuff, but still do some Python stuff.

00:01:45.080 --> 00:01:52.080
For those of you who remember or who were here last year, the photo is the race that

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:53.239
I ended up finishing.

00:01:53.239 --> 00:02:00.599
So last year's special note about me was I was training for a 100 kilometer slash 62

00:02:00.599 --> 00:02:02.519
mile trail running race.

00:02:02.519 --> 00:02:05.239
And that is me at the finish line.

00:02:05.239 --> 00:02:11.360
Unfortunately, I finished the race in...

00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:13.160
So I was at the finish line.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:15.179
This is photographic proof.

00:02:15.179 --> 00:02:21.759
But if you look up my race results on UltraSignUp, it is 26 hours and 18 minutes, which is technically

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:25.039
18 minutes past the 24 hour cutoff time.

00:02:25.039 --> 00:02:30.080
So I actually have an official did not finish as my time.

00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.919
So we'll sort of hand wave that away.

00:02:32.919 --> 00:02:34.399
It was in kilometers anyway.

00:02:34.399 --> 00:02:40.839
And maybe one day I'll do 100 units in the proper measurement in miles one day.

00:02:40.839 --> 00:02:44.679
So that's maybe a goal in a couple of years.

00:02:44.679 --> 00:02:47.240
But yes, this is 10 years of the conference.

00:02:47.240 --> 00:02:52.520
Ten years ago at the very first conference, I gave my first talk titled Interactive Ebola

00:02:52.520 --> 00:02:53.520
Plots and Shiny.

00:02:53.520 --> 00:02:57.360
Shiny was a brand new tool back then.

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:01.119
And I got to present at the very first conference.

00:03:01.119 --> 00:03:04.559
And the running joke between Jared and I was this conference has been running for many

00:03:04.559 --> 00:03:06.360
years as I was in grad school.

00:03:06.360 --> 00:03:09.119
And I'm glad that I broke that streak.

00:03:09.119 --> 00:03:11.479
But still continuing on this particular streak.

00:03:11.479 --> 00:03:15.360
So I'm very thankful for Jared for that.

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:20.919
But you've probably heard this a bunch throughout the conference already, that the R meetup

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:23.520
was the precursor to the conference.

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:28.119
And even before then, it was really just a bunch of people sitting around at a bar at

00:03:28.119 --> 00:03:30.399
a regular interval.

00:03:30.679 --> 00:03:34.160
And then eventually they named themselves in NYC Data Mafia.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.119
That eventually turned into the R meetup and now the Open Statistical Programming meetup.

00:03:39.119 --> 00:03:42.559
And then all of that accumulated into the R conference.

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:47.160
So it's been actually really cool to just see the community grow.

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:52.720
Even though I wasn't part of that initial NYC Data Mafia bar club, but I was part of

00:03:52.720 --> 00:03:53.720
the meetup.

00:03:53.720 --> 00:03:59.839
And that is sort of what I wanted to present and talk about and thank everyone today.

00:04:00.279 --> 00:04:01.399
Thank you to the community.

00:04:01.399 --> 00:04:05.240
I met hundreds of folks over the past couple of years.

00:04:05.240 --> 00:04:08.199
Before I even moved to Canada, I was up in D.C.

00:04:08.199 --> 00:04:12.279
And there's a conference there in D.C. as well.

00:04:12.279 --> 00:04:18.040
But being part of the R community and this particular community really helped me transition

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:19.040
between cities.

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:24.600
So if anyone needs to leave New York City anytime soon, just look for a local meetup

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:31.519
or start your own is sort of my recommendation to you to get acclimated to a new place.

00:04:31.519 --> 00:04:36.799
And really the conference has given me the opportunity to present and talk and refine

00:04:36.799 --> 00:04:38.679
and hone all of those skills.

00:04:38.679 --> 00:04:43.600
And also meeting all of these folks over the past couple of years or past 10 years has

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.760
opened a lot of doors for me.

00:04:46.760 --> 00:04:50.839
And so that's really my way to also say thank you for being here.

00:04:50.839 --> 00:04:55.320
But also the fact that you're here can help you as well.

00:04:55.320 --> 00:05:01.079
So participating in the meetups is a great way to sort of bolster your own professional

00:05:01.079 --> 00:05:02.399
experiences.

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:05.200
So volunteer at any of the meetups.

00:05:05.200 --> 00:05:07.720
You don't even have to volunteer at Jared's particular meetup.

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:13.959
But to be plugged into any community, an easy way to contribute is to volunteer.

00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:15.160
You can also give talks.

00:05:15.160 --> 00:05:19.359
A lot of the meetup organizers are always looking for people to give talks.

00:05:19.359 --> 00:05:25.640
So I'd say that's also a great way to contribute to the community and also help yourself in

00:05:25.640 --> 00:05:27.880
your own presentation skills.

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:30.920
And then say hello to everyone whenever you can.

00:05:30.920 --> 00:05:37.480
And then over time, you'll see a lot of benefits out of it, more so than what I can list or

00:05:37.480 --> 00:05:38.480
talk about.

00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:41.040
And it'll be different for everyone.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:46.359
So with that, I will just, you know, introduce the next block of speakers.

00:05:46.359 --> 00:05:48.959
So Wes, Max, and Hillary are the next block of speakers.

00:05:48.959 --> 00:05:54.519
And I'm sure Jared will have a fun, quirky, fun fact about all of them.

00:05:54.519 --> 00:05:56.839
So I will relinquish my time.

00:05:56.839 --> 00:06:01.320
And thank you for giving me the opportunity to continue on my streak and still be part

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:04.200
of this meetup and this conference.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:09.679
So Dan, can't see us, you can hear me.

00:06:09.679 --> 00:06:10.679
Thank you very much, Dan.

00:06:10.679 --> 00:06:12.160
It was wonderful seeing you.

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:13.160
Have a fun time there.

00:06:13.160 --> 00:06:14.760
And we look forward to seeing you next time.

00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:15.760
Yeah.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:17.559
And everyone, enjoy the conference.

00:06:17.559 --> 00:06:18.559
Great.

00:06:18.559 --> 00:06:19.559
Thank you.

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:20.559
They all gave you a big round of applause.

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:21.559
I'm not sure you could hear that through my earbud.

00:06:21.559 --> 00:06:22.559
So.

00:06:22.559 --> 00:06:23.559
All right.

00:06:23.559 --> 00:06:24.559
Bye, Dan.

00:06:24.559 --> 00:06:25.559
Thank you so much.

00:06:25.559 --> 00:06:25.559


